** Eudora Welty on Friendship as an Evolutionary Mechanism for Language (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/30/eudora-welty-norton-book-of-friend=
ship/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393030652/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CI sometimes awake in the night and think of friendship and its po=
ssibilities=2C=E2=80=9D Henry David Thoreau wrote in his diary (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2013/07/12/thoreau-on-friendship-sympathy-and-animal-c=
onsciousness/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) as he turned forty a=
nd found himself contemplating the most succulent fruits of existence. But=
 where exactly does the sweetness of friendship reside? How is it synthesi=
zed on the tongue of being?

In my recent effort to counter the commodification of the word =E2=80=9Cfr=
iend=E2=80=9D and reclaim the meaning of friendship through a taxonomy of=
 platonic relationships (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/16/friendsh=
ip/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C I was led to something rat=
her beautiful and rather forgotten that Eudora Welty (April 13=2C 1909=E2=
=80=93July 23=2C 2001) wrote on the subject in The Norton Book of Friendsh=
ip (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393030652/braipick-20?mc_cid=
=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org=
/title/norton-book-of-friendship/oclc/23357486&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_=
cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 a 1991 treasure trove of=
 literature=E2=80=99s greatest letters=2C poems=2C stories=2C essays=2C an=
d other wisdom on friendship=2C which Welty edited together with her dear=
 friend Ronald A. Sharp.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393030652/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

In her introduction to the anthology=2C Welty considers one of the central=
 perplexities of friendship =E2=80=94 the way in which it weaves itself in=
 and out of what we call love=2C a word with very particular cultural bagg=
age=2C and the way in which we=2C in our effort to disentangle this entwin=
ement into neater and more comprehensible categories=2C draw a somewhat ar=
bitrary line between the two. She writes:

Friendship and love =E2=80=A6 know each other and avail themselves of each=
 other. The solidest friendship is that of friends who love one another.

To this I would add that in the fullest and most rewarding of friendships=
=2C the two friends are always a little bit in love with one another. We n=
eed not classify the type of love as erotic=2C romantic=2C creative=2C int=
ellectual=2C spiritual=2C or some other kind=2C only to know that a great=
 friendship cycles=2C at one point or another=2C through each type.

Welty examines the singular magnetism of friendship in our lives and in ou=
r art:

=E2=80=9CFriendship=E2=80=9D is inherently a magnet. As with its own drawi=
ng power=2C it locates and draws to the surface=2C spreads before our eyes=
 poems=2C stories=2C essays=2C letters=2C in the widest variety.

[=E2=80=A6]

Certainly friendship has proved a magnet to literature=2C an everlasting m=
agnet. History=2C poetry=2C drama=2C letters have been drawn to the subjec=
t of friendship=2C not simply to celebrate it but to discover=2C perceive=
=2C learn from it the nature of ourselves=2C of humankind=2C the relations=
hips we share in our world.

Friendship has inherited its literary treasury; it lies in the language=E2=
=80=A6 And in that treasury=E2=80=99s further stories of pure gold are the=
 works of the imagination=2C some old as time=2C some coined only yesterda=
y.

Welty=E2=80=99s most salient point has to do with precisely this linguisti=
c dimension of friendship =E2=80=94 it might be the basic necessities of f=
riendship=2C she suggests=2C that sparked in us the evolutionary need for=
 language. It=E2=80=99s a notion both wonderfully poetic and rather plausi=
ble =E2=80=94 we know that music and language helped us evolve (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2011/08/03/mark-changizi-harnessed/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15=
d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and what is friendship if not learning the song=
 of another=E2=80=99s heart and singing it back to them?

Illustration by Maurice Sendak from a vintage ode to friendship (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2014/01/29/lets-be-enemies-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3D5=
24ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Janice May Udry

Welty writes:

Did friendship between human beings come about in the first place along wi=
th =E2=80=94 or through =E2=80=94 the inspiration of language? It can be s=
afe to say that when we learned to speak to=2C and listen to=2C rather tha=
n to strike or be struck by=2C our fellow human beings=2C we found somethi=
ng worth keeping alive=2C worth processing=2C for the rest of time. Might=
 it possibly have been the other way round =E2=80=94 that the promptings o=
f friendship guided us into learning to express ourselves=2C teaching ours=
elves=2C between us=2C a language to keep it by? Friendship might have bee=
n the first=2C as well as the best=2C teacher of communication. Which came=
 first=2C friendship or the spoken word? They could rise from the same pro=
mpting: to draw together=2C not to pull away=2C not to threaten any longer=
=2E

Friendship lives=2C as do we ourselves=2C in an ephemeral world. How much=
 its life depends on the written word. The English language itself is frie=
ndship=E2=80=99s greatest treasure=E2=80=A6. Do we not owe friendship=2C a=
s we owe Shakespeare=2C to language?

The Norton Book of Friendship (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393=
030652/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is itself a gre=
at treasury=2C containing such gems as Emily Dickinson=E2=80=99s letter to=
 her best friend=2C foundational meditations on friendship by Aristotle=2C=
 Cicero=2C and Montaigne=2C John Donne=E2=80=99s touching ode to a friend=
=2C and Aesop=E2=80=99s classic fables of friendship. Complement it with C=
=2ES. Lewis on the purpose of friendship (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014=
/09/08/c-s-lewis-four-loves-friendship/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) =2C Emerson on its two pillars (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/0=
8/13/emerson-on-friendship/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C An=
drew Sullivan on why friendship can be a greater gift than romantic love (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/23/love-undetectable-andrew-sullivan=
-friendship/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and John O=E2=80=
=99Donohue on the ancient Celtic notion of =E2=80=9Csoul-friend=2C=E2=80=
=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/12/anam-cara-john-o-donohue-sou=
l-friend/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) then revisit Welty on th=
e poetics of space
(https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/31/eudora-welty-on-writing-place/?m=
c_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C her impossibly charming job app=
lication to the New Yorker (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/05/12/eudor=
a-welty-new-yorker-application-letter/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) =2C and this rare recording (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/04=
/eudora-welty-reads-why-i-live-at-the-p-o/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) of her reading her quietly heartbreaking masterpiece =E2=80=9CWhy=
 I Live at the P.O.=E2=80=9D


