** Salvador Dal=C3=AD=E2=80=99s Rare 1969 Illustrations for =E2=80=9CAlice=
=E2=80=99s Adventures in Wonderland=2C=E2=80=9D Rediscovered and Resurrect=
ed (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/02/salvador-dali-alices-adventur=
es-in-wonderland/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0691170029/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

In 1865=2C a Victorian mathematician wrote a fairy tale that would go on t=
o live parallel lives as one of the world=E2=80=99s most beloved children=
=E2=80=99s books and a modernist masterwork of philosophy that mushrooms i=
ts yield of wisdom with each reading =E2=80=94 one of humanity=E2=80=99s v=
ery few works=2C alongside perhaps Leonardo da Vinci=E2=80=99s Vitruvian M=
an (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/02/08/da-vincis-ghost/?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C which subtly and seamlessly fuse art=2C sc=
ience=2C and philosophy.

Nearly a century later=2C in a 1961 lecture titled =E2=80=9CWhere Do We Go=
 from Here=2C=E2=80=9D Marcel Duchamp prophecized that tomorrow=E2=80=99s=
 emerging artists =E2=80=9Clike Alice in Wonderland =E2=80=A6 will be led=
 to pass through the looking-glass of the retina=2C to reach a more profou=
nd expression.=E2=80=9D He was the first to intuit the conceptual common g=
round between the story that the mathematician Charles Dodgson had dreamt=
 up on an afternoon boat ride (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/07/04/st=
ory-of-alice/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) a century earlier=2C=
 before he became Lewis Carroll=2C and the budding surrealist art movement=
=2C which was just beginning to find its sea legs. Duchamp=E2=80=99s insig=
ht materialized into concrete form eight years later=2C when a visionary e=
ditor at Random House commissioned surrealist kingpin Salvador Dal=C3=AD (=
May 11=2C 1904=E2=80=93January 23=2C 1989) to illustrate the Carroll class=
ic (https://www.brainpickings.org/2011/11/15/salvador-dali-alice-in-wonder=
land-1969/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) for a small=2C exclusiv=
e edition of their book-of-the-month series. Dal=C3=AD
created twelve heliogravures =E2=80=94 a frontispiece=2C which he signed i=
n every copy from the edition=2C and one illustration for each chapter of=
 the book.

Down the Rabbit Hole

For more than half a century=2C this unusual yet organic cross-pollination=
 of genius remained an almost mythic artifact=2C reserved for collectors a=
nd scholars. To mark the 150th anniversary of the beloved book=2C Princeto=
n Architectural Press brought back to life the Dal=C3=AD-illustrated Alice=
=E2=80=99s Adventures in Wonderland (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASI=
N/0691170029/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public l=
ibrary (http://www.worldcat.org/title/alices-adventures-in-wonderland/oclc=
/934635861&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 ) =E2=80=94 a crowning achievement among the greatest illustrations of th=
e Carroll masterpiece (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illus=
trations-alice-in-wonderland/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) from=
 the century and a half since its inception=2C featuring new introductions=
 by Mark Burstein=2C president of the Lewis Carroll Society of North Ameri=
ca (http://www.lewiscarroll.org/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C and mathematician Thomas Banchoff=2C who knew and collaborated with D=
al=C3=AD.

The Pool of Tears

The Caucus Race and a Long Tale

The Rabbit Sends in a Little Bill

Advice From a Caterpillar

In the introduction=2C Burstein considers the natural creative confluence=
 between Carroll and the surrealists:

For both Carroll and the surrealists=2C what some call madness could be pe=
rceived by others as wisdom. Even the creative processes of Carroll and th=
e surrealists were similar. The surrealists practiced automatism in their=
 writing and drawing; Carroll called the initial telling of the tale =E2=
=80=A6 =E2=80=9Ceffortless=2C=E2=80=9D saying that =E2=80=9Cevery such ide=
a and nearly every word of the dialogue=2C came of itself=E2=80=A6 when fa=
ncies unsought came crowding thick upon [me]=2C or at times when the jade=
d Muse was goaded into action more because she had to say something than t=
hat she had something to say.=E2=80=9D

In addition=2C collages were a serious apparatus in the surrealists=E2=80=
=99 arsenal; Carroll invented the term portmanteau =E2=80=94 combining wor=
ds =E2=80=94 and produced =E2=80=9CJabberwocky=2C=E2=80=9D the most famous=
 example of pure neologistic nonsense in the English language (or close to=
 it=2C anyway). His bestiary of mome raths=2C toves=2C and Bread-and-butte=
r-flies=2C also from Through the Looking-Glass=2C could easily have been p=
roducts of the surrealists=E2=80=99 game of Exquisite Corpse.

Dal=C3=AD himself applied a number of surrealist techniques to his interpr=
etation of the story. To represent Alice =E2=80=94 the sole character who=
 appears in every chapter =E2=80=94 he reused an image of a girl skipping=
 rope that he had first painted more than thirty years earlier. He placed=
 this strange=2C static=2C mid-motion figure=2C almost an icon=2C in each=
 of the twelve illustration =E2=80=94 a choice that was part automatism=2C=
 part cut-up technique=2C as if echoing Carroll=E2=80=99s incantation from=
 the first page: =E2=80=9CThe rest next time =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
It is next time!=E2=80=9D

Salvador Dal=C3=AD=2C Landscape with Girl Skipping Rope=2C 1936

Frontispiece for Alice=E2=80=99s Adventures in Wonderland

Pig and Pepper

Mad Tea Party

The Queen=E2=80=99s Croquet Ground

The Mock Turtle=E2=80=99s Story

The Lobster=E2=80=99s Quadrille

Alice=E2=80=99s Evidence

Complement this marvelous=2C long-awaited resurrection of the Dal=C3=AD-in=
terpreted Alice=E2=80=99s Adventures in Wonderland (http://www.amazon.com/=
exec/obidos/ASIN/0691170029/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) with the story of how the Carroll story was born (https://www.brainp=
ickings.org/2016/02/19/amanda-palmer-white-rabbit/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) and other stunning artistic interpretations (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illustrations-alice-in-wonderland/?mc_ci=
d=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of the classic tale from its 150-year h=
istory=2C then revisit Dal=C3=AD=E2=80=99s rare erotic cookbook (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2014/04/29/salvador-dali-les-diners-de-galacookbook/?=
mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and his forgotten illustrations fo=
r Don Quixote in 1946 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/09/salvador-d=
ali-illustrates-don-quixote/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C t=
he essays of Montaigne in 1947 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/08/12/s=
alvador-dali-illustrates-montaigne/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) =2C The Divine Comedy in 1957 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/03/21/=
salvador-dali-dante-divine-comedy/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C and Romeo and Juliet in 1975
(https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/01/14/salvador-dali-romeo-juliet/?mc_c=
