** Oliver Sacks on Death=2C Destiny=2C and the Redemptive Radiance of a Li=
fe Fully Lived (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/30/oliver-sacks-grat=
itude-death/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0451492935/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CTo lament that we shall not be alive a hundred years hence=2C is=
 the same folly as to be sorry we were not alive a hundred years ago=2C=E2=
=80=9D Montaigne observed in his sixteenth-century meditation on death and=
 the art of living (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/12/12/montaigne-on-=
death-and-the-art-of-living/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=
=80=9CThe greatest dignity to be found in death is the dignity of the life=
 that preceded it=2C=E2=80=9D the late surgeon and bioethicist Sherwin Nul=
and wrote half a millennium later in his foundational treatise on mortalit=
y (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/09/17/sherwin-nuland-how-we-die/?mc_=
cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

I am yet to encounter a human being who embodied and enacted these difficu=
lt truths more wholeheartedly than Oliver Sacks (July 9=2C 1933=E2=80=93Au=
gust 30=2C 2015).

He confronted death directly=2C with courageous curiosity and radiant luci=
dity=2C in one of his New York Times essays posthumously collected in the=
 small=2C enormously life-affirming book Gratitude (http://www.amazon.com/=
exec/obidos/ASIN/0451492935/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/gratitude/oclc/923548=
020&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=
=80=94 that great parting gift which gave us Dr. Sacks=E2=80=99s warm wisd=
om on the measure of living and the dignity of dying (https://www.brainpic=
kings.org/2015/11/24/oliver-sacks-gratitude-book/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) =2C edited by his partner=2C the writer and photographer B=
ill Hayes (http://www.billhayes.com/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) =2C and his friend and assistant of thirty years=2C Kate Edgar.

Oliver Sacks by Bill Hayes (http://www.billhayes.com/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

After learning of his terminal diagnosis=2C the irreplaceable Dr. Sacks pe=
ers into the depths of existence from the bittersweet platform of a long a=
nd=2C suddenly=2C immediately finite life:

I have been increasingly conscious=2C for the last 10 years or so=2C of de=
aths among my contemporaries. My generation is on the way out=2C and each=
 death I have felt as an abruption=2C a tearing away of part of myself. Th=
ere will be no one like us when we are gone=2C but then there is no one li=
ke anyone else=2C ever. When people die=2C they cannot be replaced. They l=
eave holes that cannot be filled=2C for it is the fate =E2=80=94 the genet=
ic and neural fate =E2=80=94 of every human being to be a unique individua=
l=2C to find his own path=2C to live his own life=2C to die his own death.

As he faces the end of his own path =E2=80=94 an end he had escaped narrow=
ly decades earlier=2C when he saved his own life with literature and song=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/09/oliver-sacks-a-leg-to-stand-on/=
?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 he writes:

I cannot pretend I am without fear. But my predominant feeling is one of g=
ratitude. I have loved and been loved; I have been given much and I have g=
iven something in return; I have read and traveled and thought and written=
=2E I have had an intercourse with the world=2C the special intercourse of w=
riters and readers.

Above all=2C I have been a sentient being=2C a thinking animal=2C on this=
 beautiful planet=2C and that in itself has been an enormous privilege and=
 adventure.

Complement the thoroughly transcendent Gratitude (http://www.amazon.com/ex=
ec/obidos/ASIN/0451492935/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) with Dr. Sacks on what his beloved aunt taught him about dying with di=
gnity and courage (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/05/26/oliver-sacks-o=
n-the-move-aunt-lennie/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C his en=
chanting recollection of his largehearted life (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2015/05/18/oliver-sacks-on-the-move/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) =2C and this remembrance of him (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015=
/08/31/remembering-oliver-sacks/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) w=
ritten the day of his death=2C then revisit John Updike on writing and dea=
th (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/10/john-updike-on-writing-and-de=
ath/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and this wonderful Danish chi=
ldren=E2=80=99s book about making sense of mortality (https://www.brainpic=
kings.org/2016/03/08/cry-heart-but-never-break/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) .


