** Frida Kahlo=E2=80=99s Illustrious Life=2C Illustrated (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2016/08/29/frida-kahlo-illustrated-biography-cosford-alkayat=
/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9COnly an artist can tell =E2=80=A6 what it is like for anyone who=
 gets to this planet to survive it=2C=E2=80=9D James Baldwin wrote in cont=
emplating the artist=E2=80=99s struggle for integrity (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2016/04/13/james-baldwin-the-artists-struggle-for-integrity/?mc=
_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CBeing an artist is not ju=
st about what happens when you are in the studio=2C=E2=80=9D Teresita Fern=
=C3=A1ndez argued half a century later in her spectacular commencement add=
ress on what it means to be an artist (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/=
12/29/teresita-fernandez-commencement-address/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CThe way you live=2C the people you choose to love=
 and the way you love them=2C the way you vote =E2=80=A6 will also become=
 the raw material for the art you make.=E2=80=9D

Few artists have embodied this integration more fully=2C nor more beautifu=
lly=2C than Frida Kahlo (July 6=2C 1907=E2=80=93July 13=2C 1954).

Her singular integration of life=2C love=2C and art comes alive in Frida K=
ahlo: An Illustrated Biography (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/145=
2150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public librar=
y (http://www.worldcat.org/title/frida-kahlo/oclc/927141348&referer=3Dbrie=
f_results?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) by writer Zena Alkayat=
 and artist Nina Cosford=2C part of the lovely Library of Luminaries serie=
s that gave us the illustrated biography of Virginia Woolf (https://www.br=
ainpickings.org/2016/04/12/virginia-woolf-alkayat-cosford/?mc_cid=3D524ae8=
a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and that of Jane Austen (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2016/06/01/jane-austen-illustrated-biography-alkayat-cosford/?mc_cid=
=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

The concise yet lyrical story follows Frida from her polio-scarred childho=
od in Mexico=2C to the nearly fatal accident that inflicted on her a lifet=
ime of physical pain but also sparked her foray into painting=2C to her in=
tense and complicated (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/22/frida-kahl=
o-diego-rivera-love/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) romance with=
 Diego Rivera=2C to her spirited politics (https://www.brainpickings.org/2=
013/08/02/frida-kahlos-politics/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C to her creative and critical success as one of the most original and=
 influential artists of the twentieth century. The call-and-response of pa=
in and beauty emerges as the constant chorus of her life while she transfo=
rms=2C again and again=2C trauma into transcendent art.

Alkayat writes:

At six=2C Frida fell ill with polio. She was confined to her room for nine=
 months and her right leg withered. To help her gain strength=2C her fathe=
r encouraged her to take up sports that were usually reserved for boys.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

A pivotal moment in Kahlo=E2=80=99s life=2C both physically and psychologi=
cally=2C takes place on September 17=2C 1925=2C when 18-year-old Frida is=
 nearly killed in a bus accident that drives a handrail diagonally into he=
r torso=2C from her left ribs to her uterus. Even the gore of this tragedy=
 has an almost mythic quality to it.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

It is during the anguishing and seemingly endless recovery =E2=80=94 to be=
 sure=2C being bedridden for a month is indeed an eternity of torture for=
 a teenager even without the excruciating physical pain =E2=80=94 that Fri=
da picks up painting=2C initially simply to distract herself. With the hel=
p of a mirror affixed to the canopy of her bed=2C she paints her first sel=
f-portrait =E2=80=94 a gift for Alejandro=2C her first big love.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

It takes Frida almost two years to walk again=2C and by that point she is=
 already making a living as an artist. Her longing for mentorship and prof=
essional guidance leads her to her fateful encounter with Diego Rivera (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2014/05/22/diego-rivera-frida-kahlo-meeting/?m=
c_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C who would become the great and=
 greatly troubled love of her life=2C and the recipient of her passionate=
 love letters (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/04/19/frida-kahlo-diary-=
love-letters/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Frida married Diego on August 21=2C 1929. She was twenty-two=2C he was for=
ty-two. She looked like a bright=2C beautiful bird next to the rotund=2C u=
nattractive Diego. She nicknamed him =E2=80=9CFrog-Toad.=E2=80=9D

Diego was obsessed with his craft and prized it above all else. He encoura=
ged Frida to devote herself to painting and to explore her own artistic st=
yle. But the young bride threw herself into being a good wife. She cooked=
=2C cleaned=2C and entertained.

Every lunchtime=2C she prepared a basket of food blanketed with flowers an=
d delivered it to the scaffold where Diego worked.

Even as the couple arrived in the United States in 1930=2C Frida continued=
 to dress in vibrant traditional garb inspired by South Mexico=E2=80=99s T=
ehuana matriarchs. Every single morning=2C she took painstaking care with=
 her outfit in a testament to Virginia Woolf=E2=80=99s case for clothing a=
s a vehicle for our identity and values (https://www.brainpickings.org/201=
6/08/01/virginia-woolf-orlando-clothing-gender/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) .

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

But her wardrobe was also dictated by the demands of her battered body and=
 entailed an arsenal of corsets to support her fractured torso.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Frida=E2=80=99s life continued to be marked by pain. Her longtime longing=
 for a child was violently severed by two miscarriages=2C the second of wh=
ich lasted thirteen days. While still recovering=2C she was beckoned back=
 home to the dying bedside of her mother=2C taken by breast cancer. Once a=
gain=2C she turned her trauma into raw material for art =E2=80=94 somethin=
g Marina Abramovi=C4=87 articulated beautifully (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2015/04/27/getting-there-marina-abramovic-interview/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a=
15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) a generation later =E2=80=94 and her painting took=
 on new dimensions of expressive depth.

Kahlo=E2=80=99s tireless quest for glimmers of joy included a menagerie of=
 exotic pets she loved dearly=2C perhaps because they spoke to her own sen=
se of creaturely strangeness.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

The story follows Frida=E2=80=99s life through her increasingly troubled m=
arriage with Diego=2C their divorce and remarriage=2C Diego=E2=80=99s dall=
iances=2C and Frida=E2=80=99s eventual affairs with both men (including Ma=
rxist revolutionary Leon Trotsky) and women (including jazz icon Josephine=
 Baker). Kahlo was deeply dispirited by her difficult love life=2C but thi=
s tumult of the heart found symbolic expression in her paintings and conti=
nued to shape her art=2C always so intimately entwined with her vibrant in=
terior life.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Frida=E2=80=99s old spark surfaced again in spring 1953 when a one-woman e=
xhibition was arranged in her honor. Unable to walk on the day it opened=
=2C Frida sent her four-poster bed ahead of her and arrived in grand style=
 on a stretcher. Her fans adored her=2C and the internationally celebrated=
 show did much to cement her legacy as an incomparable artist.

In a sense=2C the bed became the womb in which Kahlo=E2=80=99s creative ge=
nius and legacy were gestated =E2=80=94 she learned to paint in bed=2C met=
 her greatest critical success in bed=2C and died in bed=2C in her sleep=
=2C the following summer.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Her death occasioned the kind of collective tragedy of which Borges so mem=
orably wrote (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/24/borges-jfk-collecti=
ve-tragedy-collective-joy/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=
=94 masses of mourners grieved in public=2C and her final resting place at=
 the Place of Fine Arts was entombed by a bed of red flowers.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524=
ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Complement Frida Kahlo: An Illustrated Biography (http://www.amazon.com/ex=
ec/obidos/ASIN/1452150230/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) with the beloved artist on how love amplifies beauty (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2016/01/22/frida-kahlo-diego-rivera-love/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15=
d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C her compassionate letter to Georgia O=E2=80=99Ke=
effe (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/27/frida-kahlo-georgia-okeeffe=
-letter/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) after her American friend=
 was hospitalized for a nervous breakdown=2C and this very different pictu=
re-book (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/04/13/picture-book-biographies=
/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) about her life and spirit=2C the=
n revisit the illustrated biographies of other cultural icons: Louise Bour=
geois (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/08/cloth-lullaby-louise-bourg=
eois/?mc_cid=3D524ae8a15d&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C E.E. Cummings (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2015/03/30/enormous-smallness-e-e-cummings-matthew-bu=
